1
00:00:37,947 --> 00:00:39,938
<i>...and I'll tell you what,
the storm system's still moving west.</i>

2
00:00:40,049 --> 00:00:43,041
What are you looking at, Caroline?

3
00:00:44,086 --> 00:00:45,644
The wind, Mom.

4
00:00:48,757 --> 00:00:51,157
They say the hurricane is coming.

5
00:00:52,828 --> 00:00:55,991
I'm on a boat.

6
00:00:56,098 --> 00:00:58,362
I'm drifting.

7
00:01:00,703 --> 00:01:03,000
Can I do anything for you, Mom?

8
00:01:04,372 --> 00:01:06,237
Make anything easier?

9
00:01:07,208 --> 00:01:08,607
Oh, sugar...

10
00:01:09,143 --> 00:01:11,407
There's nothing left to do.

11
00:01:11,913 --> 00:01:13,505
Is what it is.

12
00:01:15,016 --> 00:01:17,985
Finding it harder to keep my eyes open.

13
00:01:19,954 --> 00:01:23,082
My mouth's full of cotton.

14
00:01:23,624 --> 00:01:25,751
There, there, Miss Daisy.

15
00:01:25,860 --> 00:01:28,590
You gonna scratch yourself to ribbons.

16
00:01:33,501 --> 00:01:36,299
Do you want any more
medication, Mother?

17
00:01:37,205 --> 00:01:40,402
Doctor said you could have
as much as you want.

18
00:01:40,508 --> 00:01:42,772
No need for anybody to suffer.

19
00:01:57,758 --> 00:02:00,659
A friend told me
that she never had the chance

20
00:02:00,761 --> 00:02:03,059
to say goodbye to her mother.

21
00:02:06,199 --> 00:02:08,531
- I wanted to...
- It's okay.

22
00:02:08,635 --> 00:02:12,162
I wanted to tell you
how much I'm gonna miss you so...

23
00:02:12,639 --> 00:02:13,731
Mom.

24
00:02:15,742 --> 00:02:17,505
Oh, Caroline.

25
00:02:23,316 --> 00:02:24,806
Are you afraid?

26
00:02:24,918 --> 00:02:26,613
I'm curious.

27
00:02:28,388 --> 00:02:30,015
What comes next?

28
00:02:35,561 --> 00:02:40,328
They built the train station in 1918.

29
00:02:41,367 --> 00:02:44,097
My father was there the day it opened.

30
00:02:45,771 --> 00:02:48,467
He said they had

31
00:02:50,409 --> 00:02:51,706
a tuba band playing.

32
00:02:56,482 --> 00:03:00,543
They had the finest clockmaker
in all of the South

33
00:03:01,153 --> 00:03:03,951
to build that glorious clock.

34
00:03:05,825 --> 00:03:07,383
<i>His name was...</i>

35
00:03:09,295 --> 00:03:11,092
Mr. Gateau.

36
00:03:15,468 --> 00:03:16,627
Mr. Cake.

37
00:03:19,204 --> 00:03:23,368
<i>He was married to a Creole
of Evangeline Parish</i>

38
00:03:23,475 --> 00:03:25,705
<i>and they had a son.</i>

39
00:03:27,645 --> 00:03:32,742
<i>Mr. Gateau was, from birth,
absolutely blind.</i>

40
00:03:35,019 --> 00:03:39,251
<i>When their son was old enough,
he joined the army.</i>

41
00:03:40,191 --> 00:03:44,560
<i>And they prayed God would
keep him out of harm's way.</i>

42
00:03:47,499 --> 00:03:52,232
<i>For months,
he did nothing but work on that clock.</i>

43
00:03:56,307 --> 00:03:57,740
<i>One day,</i>

44
00:03:59,110 --> 00:04:01,009
<i>a letter came.</i>

45
00:04:06,250 --> 00:04:09,981
<i>And Mr. Gateau, done for the night,</i>

46
00:04:10,687 --> 00:04:13,178
<i>went up, alone, to bed.</i>

47
00:04:15,859 --> 00:04:18,657
<i>And their son came home.</i>

48
00:04:23,834 --> 00:04:26,632
<i>They buried him in the family plot,</i>

49
00:04:26,737 --> 00:04:30,639
<i>where he would be with them
when their time came.</i>

50
00:04:32,643 --> 00:04:35,737
<i>Mr. Cake worked on his clock,</i>

51
00:04:38,615 --> 00:04:42,210
<i>laboring to finish.</i>

52
00:04:44,121 --> 00:04:47,453
<i>It was a morning to remember.</i>

53
00:04:48,758 --> 00:04:51,886
<i>Papa said
there were people everywhere.</i>

54
00:04:53,329 --> 00:04:55,889
<i>Even Teddy Roosevelt came.</i>

55
00:05:13,649 --> 00:05:15,514
It's running backwards!

56
00:05:17,153 --> 00:05:18,882
I made it that way

57
00:05:20,489 --> 00:05:22,354
so that perhaps the boys
that we lost in the war

58
00:05:22,458 --> 00:05:23,823
might stand and come home again.

59
00:05:28,731 --> 00:05:30,163
<i>Home to farm,</i>

60
00:05:31,266 --> 00:05:32,460
<i>work,</i>

61
00:05:34,035 --> 00:05:35,730
<i>have children.</i>

62
00:05:39,040 --> 00:05:41,508
<i>To live long, full lives.</i>

63
00:05:44,679 --> 00:05:47,375
Perhaps my own son
might come home again.

64
00:05:56,057 --> 00:05:58,582
I'm sorry if I've offended anybody.

65
00:06:00,161 --> 00:06:02,425
I hope you enjoy my clock.

66
00:06:03,331 --> 00:06:07,199
<i>Mr. Cake was never seen again.</i>

67
00:06:11,573 --> 00:06:15,975
<i>Some say he died of a broken heart.</i>

68
00:06:17,745 --> 00:06:20,009
<i>Some say he went to sea.</i>

69
00:06:25,152 --> 00:06:26,312
Excuse me.

70
00:06:26,420 --> 00:06:28,980
Do you mind if I make a call?
Somebody's watching my little boy.

71
00:06:29,089 --> 00:06:30,317
Sure.

72
00:06:40,567 --> 00:06:42,797
I hope I haven't disappointed you.

73
00:06:42,903 --> 00:06:45,997
You couldn't disappoint me.

74
00:06:47,474 --> 00:06:52,343
Well, I know I don't have much
to show for myself.

75
00:06:54,915 --> 00:06:57,349
Find my dark suitcase.

76
00:07:01,721 --> 00:07:04,622
There's a diary.

77
00:07:06,793 --> 00:07:07,851
This?

78
00:07:10,596 --> 00:07:13,497
Could you read it to me?

79
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:16,298
Is this what you want to do?

80
00:07:16,402 --> 00:07:20,304
I tried to read it
a hundred different times.

81
00:07:21,274 --> 00:07:23,265
Mom, it's not exactly...

82
00:07:23,376 --> 00:07:26,777
It's just the sound of your voice, darling.

83
00:07:27,413 --> 00:07:28,607
Okay.

84
00:07:31,751 --> 00:07:34,720
It's dated April 4th, 1985.

85
00:07:35,855 --> 00:07:38,187
And it says New Orleans.

86
00:07:38,291 --> 00:07:41,021
"This is my last will and testament.

87
00:07:41,127 --> 00:07:45,324
"I don't have much to leave,
few possessions, no money, really.

88
00:07:45,731 --> 00:07:50,964
"I will go out of this world the same way
I came in, alone and with nothing.

89
00:07:51,636 --> 00:07:53,472
"All I have is my story,

90
00:07:53,605 --> 00:07:57,006
"and I'm writing it now
while I still remember it.

91
00:07:57,809 --> 00:08:00,972
"My name is Benjamin.
Benjamin Button. "

92
00:08:01,346 --> 00:08:04,440
<i>And I was born under
unusual circumstances.</i>

93
00:08:05,417 --> 00:08:07,647
<i>The First World War had ended,</i>

94
00:08:08,353 --> 00:08:12,221
<i>and I've been told it was
an especially good night to be born.</i>

95
00:08:13,859 --> 00:08:16,020
Thank God it's over!

96
00:08:16,128 --> 00:08:17,925
We won the war!

97
00:08:32,843 --> 00:08:34,640
The Great War is over!

98
00:08:46,924 --> 00:08:47,948
What are you doing here?

99
00:08:48,058 --> 00:08:49,355
Thomas,

100
00:08:50,594 --> 00:08:52,027
I'm afraid she's going to die.

101
00:08:52,129 --> 00:08:53,289
What?

102
00:08:54,465 --> 00:08:58,094
That's enough.
All of you, get away from her.

103
00:09:01,305 --> 00:09:04,399
I came as quickly as I could.
The streets are filled with people.

104
00:09:04,508 --> 00:09:05,770
Thomas.

105
00:09:06,277 --> 00:09:08,871
Promise me he has a place.

106
00:09:11,282 --> 00:09:12,407
Yeah.

107
00:09:13,783 --> 00:09:15,774
<i>She gave her life for me.</i>

108
00:09:16,820 --> 00:09:19,789
<i>And for that, I am forever grateful.</i>

109
00:09:29,399 --> 00:09:30,798
Mr. Button.

110
00:09:46,115 --> 00:09:47,343
Thomas!

111
00:09:47,450 --> 00:09:48,678
Thomas.

112
00:09:50,687 --> 00:09:52,848
Thomas? Where are you going?

113
00:10:21,483 --> 00:10:23,815
Hey! What are you doing there?

114
00:10:25,053 --> 00:10:27,078
What do you have there?

115
00:11:24,745 --> 00:11:27,076
- Come on, Queenie.
- Now, Mr. Weathers!

116
00:11:27,180 --> 00:11:30,547
Come on, now, you know I ain't got
nothing but work to do around here.

117
00:11:30,650 --> 00:11:32,914
- Come on. Just take some time.
- Stop all this foolishness.

118
00:11:36,122 --> 00:11:37,885
The air is sweet.

119
00:11:42,329 --> 00:11:45,389
You look very handsome tonight,
Miss Queenie.

120
00:11:46,733 --> 00:11:48,860
Handsome as I've ever seen.

121
00:11:50,303 --> 00:11:52,533
The brown matches your eyes.

122
00:11:52,639 --> 00:11:53,970
Oh, hush!

123
00:11:55,442 --> 00:11:59,572
Let's see here.
You ain't no slouch yourself.

124
00:12:08,154 --> 00:12:09,951
Hambert's back in town.

125
00:12:10,056 --> 00:12:13,821
He came home legless, but he's home.

126
00:12:14,827 --> 00:12:17,455
I know you were sweet on him one time.

127
00:12:17,997 --> 00:12:19,862
Sweeter than I should've been.

128
00:12:19,965 --> 00:12:21,865
Miss Simone messed herself.

129
00:12:21,967 --> 00:12:23,195
Oh, sweet Jesus.

130
00:12:23,302 --> 00:12:25,827
She got to stop doing that
or it's diapers for her.

131
00:12:25,938 --> 00:12:27,963
- I'll be right there, Miss Jameson!
- Now, Queenie, now come on.

132
00:12:28,073 --> 00:12:30,633
Okay, Queenie'll be right there.

133
00:12:30,743 --> 00:12:32,005
It's awful nice out here.

134
00:12:32,111 --> 00:12:35,308
Come on out back for a moment.
Take your mind off things.

135
00:12:35,414 --> 00:12:36,438
You're so bad.

136
00:12:36,548 --> 00:12:39,016
- What in God's name?
- What's this?

137
00:12:49,395 --> 00:12:51,625
Oh, the Lord done something here.

138
00:12:51,730 --> 00:12:55,221
Hope I didn't hurt it none
stepping on it like that.

139
00:12:55,333 --> 00:12:56,857
We best leave that for the police.

140
00:12:56,968 --> 00:12:58,458
Poor baby.

141
00:12:59,303 --> 00:13:00,634
I'll go.

142
00:13:01,305 --> 00:13:04,968
It's for sure nobody wanted to keep it.
Come on, baby.

143
00:13:07,645 --> 00:13:10,079
Queenie? Where are you, Queenie?

144
00:13:10,181 --> 00:13:12,115
Hold your water! You go deal with it.

145
00:13:12,216 --> 00:13:14,309
Okay. No, go, I'll be back.

146
00:13:15,186 --> 00:13:18,451
Queenie, Apple, she went and messed
herself all over again!

147
00:13:18,556 --> 00:13:20,421
Jane Childress, start her a bath!

148
00:13:20,525 --> 00:13:22,584
And mind your own business,
Mrs. Duprey.

149
00:13:22,694 --> 00:13:24,491
You'll be messing yourself
soon enough.

150
00:13:24,595 --> 00:13:26,153
Somebody stole my necklace.

151
00:13:26,264 --> 00:13:29,199
Okay. All right, Mrs. Hollister,
I'll be right with you, okay?

152
00:13:29,300 --> 00:13:31,495
Go on back upstairs, hear?

153
00:13:37,809 --> 00:13:40,333
You are as ugly as an old pot

154
00:13:40,444 --> 00:13:42,105
but you're still a child of God.

155
00:13:42,212 --> 00:13:44,578
Queenie, Apple,
she won't take a bath without you!

156
00:13:44,681 --> 00:13:46,148
Mercy.

157
00:13:46,249 --> 00:13:48,217
I'll be right there!

158
00:13:51,254 --> 00:13:54,189
Okay. You just wait right here
for me now, okay?

159
00:13:57,527 --> 00:14:02,157
My sister gave me those pearls.
I can't find them anywhere.

160
00:14:02,265 --> 00:14:06,099
- Somebody's been stealing my jewelry.
- They're right here, Mrs. Hollister. See?

161
00:14:06,203 --> 00:14:09,502
Right around your pretty white neck.
Now, come on. Hush all that noise.

162
00:14:09,606 --> 00:14:12,200
- Is Dr. Rose still here?
- I don't know.

163
00:14:15,011 --> 00:14:16,308
Your heart is strong.

164
00:14:16,413 --> 00:14:19,382
You just want to avoid
any undue stimulation.

165
00:14:19,983 --> 00:14:23,077
I trust you ladies
will help me out with that?

166
00:14:23,186 --> 00:14:26,313
I have something.
Could you come downstairs?

167
00:14:30,025 --> 00:14:33,722
Never seen anything like it.
Nearly blind from cataracts.

168
00:14:33,829 --> 00:14:37,890
I'm not sure if he can hear.
His bones indicate severe arthritis.

169
00:14:38,734 --> 00:14:43,103
His skin has lost all elasticity,
and his hands and feet are ossified.

170
00:14:43,205 --> 00:14:47,801
He shows all the deterioration,
the infirmities, not of a newborn,

171
00:14:47,910 --> 00:14:50,538
but of a man well in his 80s
on his way to the grave.

172
00:14:50,646 --> 00:14:51,635
He's dying?

173
00:14:51,747 --> 00:14:54,978
His body is failing him
before his life's begun.

174
00:14:57,353 --> 00:14:58,786
Where'd he come from?

175
00:14:58,888 --> 00:15:03,257
My sister's child. From Lafayette.
She had an unfortunate adventure.

176
00:15:03,359 --> 00:15:07,261
The poor child, he got the worst of it.
Come out white.

177
00:15:10,298 --> 00:15:14,894
There are places for unwanted babies
like these, Queenie.

178
00:15:15,537 --> 00:15:18,199
No room for another mouth to feed here.

179
00:15:18,306 --> 00:15:20,831
The Nolan Foundation,
despite their good intentions,

180
00:15:20,942 --> 00:15:23,706
thinks this place is
a large nuisance as it is.

181
00:15:23,812 --> 00:15:24,891
- A baby...
- You said he don't have long.

182
00:15:24,926 --> 00:15:25,971
- A baby...
- You said he don't have long.

183
00:15:26,080 --> 00:15:30,642
Queenie, some creatures
aren't meant to survive.

184
00:15:34,055 --> 00:15:37,786
No, this baby, he is a miracle.
That's for certain.

185
00:15:37,892 --> 00:15:40,884
Just not the kind of miracle
one hopes to see.

186
00:15:43,932 --> 00:15:46,423
Y'all listen. Y'all listen up here.

187
00:15:47,202 --> 00:15:48,226
We're gonna have us a visitor

188
00:15:48,336 --> 00:15:51,430
that's gonna be staying with us
for a little while.

189
00:15:51,539 --> 00:15:55,235
My sister had a child
and she couldn't see right by it, so...

190
00:15:57,511 --> 00:15:59,240
He's known as...

191
00:16:02,516 --> 00:16:03,813
Benjamin.

192
00:16:04,484 --> 00:16:05,781
Benjamin.

193
00:16:06,687 --> 00:16:09,622
He's not a well child, so we're gonna
have to take good care of him.

194
00:16:09,723 --> 00:16:10,781
I had 10 children.

195
00:16:10,891 --> 00:16:14,224
There's not a baby I can't care for.
Let me see him.

196
00:16:16,430 --> 00:16:20,059
God in Heaven.
He looks just like my ex-husband.

197
00:16:20,901 --> 00:16:23,529
Look, he's prematurely old.

198
00:16:24,037 --> 00:16:27,564
Dr. Rose said he ain't got much more
time on this earth.

199
00:16:27,908 --> 00:16:29,034
Join the club.

200
00:16:34,147 --> 00:16:35,614
He's smiling!

201
00:16:42,388 --> 00:16:45,050
Hambert sends his
remembrances to you.

202
00:16:54,867 --> 00:16:57,199
Are you right out of your mind?

203
00:16:58,504 --> 00:17:01,871
I know you ain't got all the parts
it takes to make one of your own,

204
00:17:01,974 --> 00:17:03,202
but this ain't yours to keep.

205
00:17:03,309 --> 00:17:05,573
It may not even be humankind.

206
00:17:14,720 --> 00:17:17,120
Mr. Weathers, come back here.

207
00:17:19,458 --> 00:17:20,686
Please.

208
00:17:37,042 --> 00:17:39,602
You never know what's coming for you.

209
00:17:49,621 --> 00:17:51,987
<i>It seemed I had found a home.</i>

210
00:17:55,160 --> 00:17:56,218
Is any of this true?

211
00:17:56,328 --> 00:17:59,695
You have such a lovely voice.

212
00:18:00,265 --> 00:18:04,929
Mom, it's an ancient streetcar token.

213
00:18:06,637 --> 00:18:09,765
That clock just kept going,

214
00:18:10,774 --> 00:18:14,972
year after year after year.

215
00:18:19,283 --> 00:18:21,183
<i>But I didn't know I was a child.</i>

216
00:18:21,285 --> 00:18:23,753
Same old crap every day.

217
00:18:24,655 --> 00:18:27,419
<i>I thought I was like everyone else there.</i>

218
00:18:28,425 --> 00:18:30,586
<i>An old man in the twilight of his life.</i>

219
00:18:30,694 --> 00:18:33,026
Could you make him stop that?

220
00:18:34,031 --> 00:18:37,091
Stop banging that fork.
It's used for eating, not for playing with.

221
00:18:37,201 --> 00:18:40,034
And use your napkin, please,
Mr. Benjamin.

222
00:18:42,406 --> 00:18:43,668
Queenie!

223
00:18:55,752 --> 00:18:57,049
Hey, boy.

224
00:19:04,427 --> 00:19:06,725
<i>Always had a healthy curiosity.</i>

225
00:19:07,897 --> 00:19:11,355
<i>What was up the street?
Or around the next corner?</i>

226
00:19:13,236 --> 00:19:14,533
Go get him!

227
00:19:14,637 --> 00:19:18,334
Benjamin! That is dangerous.
Come back over here.

228
00:19:19,075 --> 00:19:20,804
Stay put, child.

229
00:19:23,179 --> 00:19:25,113
<i>I loved her very much.</i>

230
00:19:25,915 --> 00:19:27,542
<i>She was my mother.</i>

231
00:19:27,650 --> 00:19:28,810
Mama.

232
00:19:29,519 --> 00:19:30,645
Mama.

233
00:19:31,454 --> 00:19:35,220
Some days I feel different
than the day before.

234
00:19:36,658 --> 00:19:40,685
Everybody feels different about
themselves, one way or another.

235
00:19:41,663 --> 00:19:43,961
But we're all going the same way.

236
00:19:45,333 --> 00:19:48,996
Just taking different roads to get there,
that's all.

237
00:19:49,104 --> 00:19:51,572
You're on your own road, Benjamin.

238
00:19:54,342 --> 00:19:57,004
Mama? How much longer I got?

239
00:19:57,512 --> 00:20:00,811
Just be thankful
for what you're given, hear?

240
00:20:00,916 --> 00:20:03,976
You're already here longer
than you're supposed to.

241
00:20:06,888 --> 00:20:09,789
<i>Some nights, I'd have to sleep alone.</i>

242
00:20:18,500 --> 00:20:20,160
<i>I didn't mind.</i>

243
00:20:21,068 --> 00:20:23,798
<i>I would listen to the house breathing.</i>

244
00:20:25,005 --> 00:20:27,064
<i>All those people sleeping.</i>

245
00:20:28,542 --> 00:20:30,737
<i>I felt safe.</i>

246
00:20:51,599 --> 00:20:54,193
<i>It was a place of great routine.</i>

247
00:20:54,301 --> 00:20:57,202
<i>Every morning at 5:30,
no matter the weather,</i>

248
00:20:57,304 --> 00:21:01,365
<i>General Winslow, U.S. Army, Retired,
would raise the flag.</i>

249
00:21:04,245 --> 00:21:08,203
<i>Mrs. Sybil Wagner,
once an opera singer of some note,</i>

250
00:21:08,314 --> 00:21:10,942
